Definition: A furanochromone that is furo[3,2-<ital>g</ital>]chromen-5-one which is substituted at positions 4 and 7 by methoxy and methyl groups, respectively. Found in the toothpick-plant, <ital>Ammi visnaga</ital>.
An aminoglycoside sulfate salt resulting from the reaction of ribostamycin  with sulfuric acid.
An indole alkaloid that is vobasan in which the bridgehead methyl group is substituted by a methoxycarbonyl group and an additional oxo substituent is present in the 3-position.
A heptitol that is heptane-1,2,3,4,5,6,7-heptol that has <stereo>R</stereo>-configuration at positions 2, 3, 5 and 6.
A cyanogenic glycoside that is (4<stereo>R</stereo>)-4-hydroxycyclopent-2-ene-1-carbonitrile attached to a <stereo>beta</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-glucopyranosyloxy at position 1.

A triazole-based antifungal agent used for the treatment of esophageal candidiasis, invasive pulmonary aspergillosis, and serious fungal infections caused by <ital>Scedosporium apiospermum</ital> and <ital>Fusarium</ital> spp. It is an inhibitor of cytochrome P450 2C9 (CYP2C9) and CYP3A4.
A fatty acid ester resulting from the condensation of the carboxy group of a fatty acid with the alcoholic hydroxy group of a fatty alcohol.
A member of the class of coumestans that is coumestan with hydroxy substituents as positions 1, 8 and 9 and a methoxy substituent at position 3.

A member of the class of  7-hydroxyisoflavones that is isoflavone substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 5, 7 and 4' and a prenyl group at position 6. It has been isolated from <ital>Ficus mucuso</ital>.

A  withanolide that is 5,6:22,26-diepoxyergosta-2,24-diene-1,26-dione substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 4 and 22 (the 4<stereo>beta</stereo>,5<stereo>beta</stereo>,6<stereo>beta</stereo>,22<stereo>R</stereo> stereoisomer). Isolated from <ital>Tubocapsicum anomalum</ital> and <ital>Withania somnifera</ital>, it exhibits cytotoxic activity.
A dihydroxy- and monomethoxy-flavone in which the hydroxy groups are positioned at C-5 and C-7 and the methoxy group is at C-8.
A purine ribonucleoside 5'-diphosphate having xanthosine as the nucleobase.
The xanthosine 5'-phosphate in which the 5'-phosphate is a triphosphate group.
A quinolinemonocarboxylic acid that is quinoline-2-carboxylic acid substituted by hydroxy groups at C-4 and C-8.
An indole alkaloid with <greek>alpha</greek><smallsub>2</smallsub>-adrenoceptor antagonist activity. It is produced by <ital>Corynanthe johimbe</ital> and <ital>Rauwolfia serpentina</ital>.

The dipeptide obtained by coupling <element>N</element>-benzyloxycarbonyl-<stereo>L</stereo>-tyrosine with the hydroxamic acid derivative of <stereo>L</stereo>-leucine. It is an inhibitor of the metallo-protease enzyme, pseudolysin (EC 3.4.24.36).
A pyrimidine 2',3'-dideoxyribonucleoside compound having cytosine as the nucleobase.
A pyrazolo[1,5-<ital>a</ital>]pyrimidine having a nitrile group at position 3 and a 3-(<element>N</element>-ethylacetamido)phenyl substituent at the 7-position.
A sesquiterpene lactone that is decahydroazuleno[4,5-<ital>b</ital>]furan-2(3<element>H</element>)-one substituted by methylidene groups at positions 3, 6 and 9 and a hydroxy group at position 8.
A macrolide comprising a fourteen-membered lactone fused to 1,3-dihydroxybenzene; a potent estrogenic metabolite produced by some <ital>Giberella</ital> species.
A pyrimidine 2',3'-dideoxyribonucleoside compound having a 3'-azido substituent and thymine as the nucleobase.

A member of the class of 1-benzothiophenes that is 1-benzothiophene in which the hydrogen at position 2 is replaced by a 1-[carbamoyl(hydroxy)amino]ethyl group. A selective 5-lipoxygenase inhibitor, it inhibits the formation of leukotrienes LTB4, LTC4, LDT4, and LTE4. It is used for the management of chronic asthma.

2-Methylcyclohexa-1,3-diene in which a hydrogen at the 5 position is substituted (<stereo>R</stereo> configuration) by a 6-methyl-hept-5-en-2-yl group (<stereo>S</stereo> configuration). It is a sesquiterpene found in the dried rhizomes of Indonesian ginger, <ital>Zingiber officinale</ital>.
A piperazine compound having 1,2-benzothiazol-3-yl- and 2-(6-chloro-1,3-dihydro-2-oxindol-5-yl)ethyl substituents attached to the nitrogen atoms.

A member of the class of tryptamines that is <element>N</element>,<element>N</element>-dimethyltryptamine in which the hydrogen at position 5 of the indole ring has been replaced by a [(4<stereo>S</stereo>)-2-oxo-1,3-oxazolidin-4-yl]methyl group. A serotonin 5-HT1 B and D receptor agonist, it is used for the treatment of migraine.

An imidazo[1,2-<ital>a</ital>]pyridine compound having a 4-tolyl group at the 2-position, an <element>N</element>,<element>N</element>-dimethylcarbamoylmethyl group at the 3-position and a methyl substituent at the 6-position.
The hemitartrate salt of zolpidem.
A 1,2-benzoxazole compound having a sulfamoylmethyl substituent at the 3-position.

A <locant>beta</locant>-hydroxy ketone that is 5-hydroxydecan-3-one substituted by a 4-hydroxy-3-methoxyphenyl moiety at position 1; believed to inhibit adipogenesis. It is a constituent of fresh ginger.
A  proanthocyanidin isolated from <ital>Cinnamomum cassia</ital>.
A pentacyclic triterpenoid that is ursane which contains a double bond between positions 12 and 13 and in which the hydrogen at the 3<stereo>beta</stereo> position is substituted by a hydroxy group.
A sesquiterpene that is cedrane which has a double bond between positions 8 and 9.

A sesquiterpene that is tricyclo[4.4.0.0<smallsup>2,7</smallsup>]dec-3-ene bearing an isopropyl substituent at position 8 and two methyl substituents at positions 1 and 3 (the 1<stereo>S</stereo>,6<stereo>S</stereo>,7<stereo>S</stereo>,8<stereo>S</stereo>-diastereomer).
A carotenol, the structure of which is (6'<stereo>R</stereo>)-<greek>beta</greek>,<greek>epsilon</greek>-carotene hydroxy-substituted at C-3' with <stereo>R</stereo>-stereochemistry.
An <greek>alpha</greek>-curcumene that has <stereo>R</stereo> configuration at the chiral centre.

A conjugated linolenic acid having three fully-conjugated double bonds at positions 9, 11 and 13, in <stereo>cis</stereo>, <stereo>trans</stereo> and <stereo>trans</stereo> configurations, respectively.

Ergotaman bearing hydroxy, isopropyl, and 2-methylpropyl groups at the 12', 2' and 5' positions, respectively, and oxo groups at positions 3', 6', and 18. It is a natural ergot alkaloid. Ergocryptine discussed in the literature prior to 1967, when <greek>beta</greek>-ergocryptine was separated from <greek>alpha</greek>-ergocryptine, is now referred to as <greek>alpha</greek>-ergocryptine.
A eudesmane sesquiterpenoid in which the eudesmane skeleton carries a hydroxy substituent at C-11 and has a double bond between C-3 and C-4.
Any fatty acid with a hydroxy functional group in the <stereo>alpha</stereo>- or 2-position.
A methyl ketone that is <greek>alpha</greek>-ionone in which a hydrogen at position 5 of the cyclohex-2-en-1-yl ring is substituted by a methyl group.
A naphthol carrying a hydroxy group at position 1.

An organic heterotetracyclic compound that is 4'-demethylpodophyllotoxin which is substituted by a hydroxy group at position 10 but which is lacking the hydroxy group at position 9. It is found as a glucoside in the rhizomes of <ital>Podophyllum peltatum</ital>.

One of three isomeric monoterpenes differing in the positions of their two double bonds (<greek>beta</greek>- and <greek>gamma</greek>-terpinene being the others). In <greek>alpha</greek>-terpinene the  double bonds are at the 1- and 3-positions of the <ital>p</ital>-menthane skeleton.

A pentacyclic triterpenoid that is oleanane substituted at the 3<stereo>beta</stereo>-position by a hydroxy group and containing a double bond between positions 12 and 13. It is one of the most commonly occurring triterpenoids in higher plants.
The <stereo>cis</stereo>-isomer of asarone.

A <greek>beta</greek>-caryophyllene in which the stereocentre adjacent to the exocyclic double bond has <stereo>S</stereo> configuration while the remaining stereocentre has <stereo>R</stereo> configuration. It is the most commonly occurring form of <greek>beta</greek>-caryophyllene, occurring in many essential oils, particularly oil of cloves.
The (6<stereo>R</stereo>)-enantiomer of <greek>beta</greek>-chamigrene.
A citronellol that is oct-6-ene substituted by a hydroxy group at position 1 and methyl groups at positions 3 and 7 (the 3<stereo>R</stereo>-enantiomer).
A carotenol that exhibits antioxidant activity. It has been isolated from fruits such as papaya and oranges.
A tricyclic sesquiterpene, a constituent of the leaf oil cubebene obtained from a variety of species of flowering plant.

A polypeptide consisting of 31 amino acid residues in the sequence Tyr-Gly-Gly-Phe-Met-Thr-Ser-Glu-Lys-Ser-Gln-Thr-Pro-Leu-Val-Thr-Leu-Phe-Lys-Asn-Ala-Ile-Ile-Lys-Asn-Ala-Tyr-Lys-Lys-Gly-Glu.  It is an endogenous opioid peptide neurotransmitter found in the neurons of both the central and peripheral nervous system and results from processing of the precursor protein proopiomelanocortin (POMC).

A carbobicyclic compound that is <stereo>trans</stereo>-decalin substituted at positions 2, 4a, and 8 by 2-hydroxypropan-2-yl, methyl and methylidene groups, respectively (the 2<stereo>R</stereo>,4a<stereo>R</stereo>,8a<stereo>S</stereo>-diastereoisomer).
A <greek>beta</greek>-farnesene in which the double bond at position 6-7 has <stereo>E</stereo> configuration. It is the major or sole alarm pheromone in most species of aphid.

A benzochromenone that is 3,4-dihydro-2<element>H</element>-benzo[<ital>h</ital>]chromene-5,6-dione substituted by geminal methyl groups at position 2. Isolated from <ital>Tabebuia avellanedae</ital>, it exhibits antineoplastic and anti-inflammatory activities.
A naphthol carrying a hydroxy group at position 2.
The <stereo>trans</stereo>-stereoisomer of ocimene.

A sesquiterpene and carbobicyclic compound that is bicyclo[2.2.1]heptane in which the hydrogens at position 3 are substituted by a methylidene group, while the 2-<stereo>exo</stereo>- and 2-<stereo>endo</stereo>- hydrogens are subsitituted by 2-methylpent-2-en-5-yl and methyl groups, respectively (the 1<stereo>S</stereo>,2<stereo>R</stereo>,4<stereo>R</stereo> enantiomer).
An optically active form of <greek>beta</greek>-selinene having (+)-(4a<stereo>R</stereo>,7<stereo>R</stereo>,8a<stereo>S</stereo>)-configuration.

A monoterpenoid that is cyclohepta-2,4,6-trien-1-one substituted by a hydroxy group at position 2 and an isopropyl group at position 4. Isolated from <ital>Thuja plicata</ital> and <ital>Chamaecyparis obtusa</ital>, it exhibits antimicrobial activities.
A dTDP-sugar having 3-amino-3,4,6-trideoxy-<stereo>alpha</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-glucose as the sugar component.
A dTDP-sugar having <stereo>beta</stereo>-<stereo>L</stereo>-mycarose as the sugar component.
Elementary particle not affected by the strong force having a spin <frac12/>, a negative elementary charge and a rest mass of 0.000548579903(13) u, or 0.51099906(15) MeV.

A germacranolide with formula C<smallsub>17</smallsub>H<smallsub>22</smallsub>O<smallsub>4</smallsub>, originally isolated from <ital>Liriodendron tulipifera</ital>. It exhibits anti-cancer and anti-oxidant properties.
A stilbenoid that is the (<minus/>)-<stereo>trans</stereo>-stereoisomer of <greek>epsilon</greek>-viniferin, obtained by cyclodimerisation of <stereo>trans</stereo>-resveratrol.
A dipeptide composed of 3-cyano-<stereo>L</stereo>-alanine and <stereo>L</stereo>-glutamine joined by a peptide linkage formed from the side-chain of glutamine.

A chlorocyclohexene that is cyclohexene which carries 5 chlorines at positions 1,3,4,5 and 6, respectively. It has (3<stereo>R</stereo>,4<stereo>S</stereo>,5<stereo>S</stereo>,6<stereo>R</stereo>) configuration.

One of three isomeric monoterpenes differing in the positions of their two double bonds (<greek>alpha</greek>- and <greek>beta</greek>-terpinene being the others). In <greek>gamma</greek>-terpinene the double bonds are at the 1- and 4-positions of the <ital>p</ital>-menthane skeleton.
An organic 3-carboxyphenyl phosphonate monoester.
A <element>N</element>-arylpiperazine that is piperazine carrying a 3-chlorophenyl substituent at position 1. It is a metabolite of the antidepressant drug trazodone.
A methylbenzoic acid carrying a methyl substituent at position 3.
A <stereo>L</stereo>-phenylalanine derivative that is <stereo>L</stereo>-phenylalanine in which the hydrogen at position 4 on the benzene ring is replaced by a fluoro group.

A sulfonamide that consists of <element>N</element>,<element>N</element>-dimethyltryptamine bearing an additional (<element>N</element>-methylsulfamoyl)methyl substituent at position 5. Selective agonist for a vascular 5-HT<smallsub>1</smallsub> receptor subtype (probably a member of the 5-HT<smallsub>1D</smallsub> family). Used (in the form of its succinate salt) for the acute treatment of migraine with or without aura in adults.
The (3<stereo>S</stereo>)-diastereomer of 3-hydroxy-<stereo>L</stereo>-aspartic acid.
An unsaturated fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of <stereo>trans</stereo>-dec-2-enoic acid.
The (4<stereo>S</stereo>)-enantiomer of perillyl alcohol.
A member of the class of chalcones that is chalcone substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 2', 3, 4, 4', and 6'.
The (<stereo>E</stereo>)-isomer of cinnamoyl-CoA.
The (<stereo>R</stereo>)-enantiomer of 2-benzylsuccinyl-CoA.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of (<stereo>R</stereo>)-3-[(<stereo>R</stereo>)-3-hydroxybutanoyloxy]butanoic acid
The conjugate base of (<stereo>R</stereo>)-3-hydroxybutyric acid.
An organophosphate oxoanion that is the trianion of (<stereo>R</stereo>)-5-phosphopantothenic acid arising from deprotonation of the carboxy and phosphate OH groups; major species at pH 7.3
A (2<stereo>R</stereo>)-2-hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of (<stereo>R</stereo>)-3-phenyllactic acid.
An acyl-CoA having (<stereo>R</stereo>)-phenyllactoyl as the <stereo>S</stereo>-acyl group.
A monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxy group of (<stereo>S</stereo>)-4-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid.
The conjugate base of (<stereo>S</stereo>)-3-hydroxybutyric acid.
The (<stereo>S</stereo>)-enantiomer of carnitine.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 1,4-dihydroxy-2-naphthoic acid.
A glycerophosphocholine having an unspecified <element>O</element>-acyl substituent at the 1-position of the glycerol fragment.
The conjugate base of 10-hydroxycapric acid.
The conjugate base of 13-hydroxydocosanoic acid.
An adenosine 5'-phosphate derivative that has the structure of coenzyme A dephosphorylated at C-3' and with a 5-triphospho-<stereo>alpha</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-ribosyl substituent at C-2'.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion resulting from deprotonation of both carboxy groups of 2,3,4,5-tetrahydrodipicolinic acid.
Conjugate base of 2,5-didehydro-<stereo>D</stereo>-gluconic acid.
A glycerophosphocholine having an unspecified acyl group attached at the 2-position.
The 5-<element>N</element>-formyl derivative of 2,5-diamino-6-ribosylamino-4(3<element>H</element>)-pyrimidinone 5'-phosphate.
A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion that results from the removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of 2-dehydropantoic acid.
The <stereo>alpha</stereo>-anomer of 2-deoxy-<stereo>D</stereo>-ribofuranose 1-phosphate.
A coumarate that is the conjugate base of 2-coumaric acid.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion resulting from the removal of a proton from both of the carboxylic acid groups of 2-hydroxyglutaric acid.
An alk-2-enoyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 2-methylbut-2-enoic acid.

A group obtained by removing the hydroxy group from the hemiacetal function of 3-(2,4-bis[<element>N</element>-acetyl-<stereo>beta</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-glucosaminyl]-<stereo>alpha</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-mannosyl)-<stereo>beta</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-mannose.
A 3-<ital>sn</ital>-glycerophosphoserine compound having acyl substituents at the 1- and 2-hydroxy positions.

An <locant>alpha</locant>,<locant>omega</locant> dicarboxyacyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with one of the carboxy groups of 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaric acid.
A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of <element>N</element>-carbamoyl-<locant>beta</locant>-alanine arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.
Conjugate base of 3<stereo>alpha</stereo>,7<stereo>alpha</stereo>-dihydroxy-12-oxo-5<stereo>beta</stereo>-cholanic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A benzoate resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of 4-(<stereo>beta</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-glucosyloxy)benzoic acid.

A group obtained by removing the hydroxy group from the hemiacetal function of <element>N</element>-acetyl-<stereo>beta</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-glucosaminyl-(1<arrow>right</arrow>4)-<stereo>beta</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-mannose.
An arenesulfonate that is the conjugate base of 4-(hydroxymethyl)benzenesulfonic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the sulfonic acid group.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 4-acetamidobutanoic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.
The conjugate base of <locant>gamma</locant>-amino-<locant>beta</locant>-hydroxybutyric acid arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A butenolide having a carboxymethylene group at the 4-position.
An arenesulfonate that is the conjugate base of 4-formylbenzenesulfonic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the sulfonic acid group.
An  oxo dicarboxylate that is the conjugate base of 4-oxohex-2-enedioic acid.
A tricarboxylic acid trianion that is the conjugate base of 5-hydroxypenta-2,4-diene-1,2,5-tricarboxylic acid.
An oxo fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of 5-oxohexanoic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.

A group obtained by removing the hydroxy group from the hemiacetal function of <stereo>alpha</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-mannosyl-(1<arrow>right</arrow>6)-<stereo>beta</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-mannose.
The <stereo>alpha</stereo>-anomer of 6-(<element>N</element>-acetyl-<stereo>D</stereo>-glucosaminyl)-1-phosphatidyl-1<stereo>D</stereo>-<ital>myo</ital>-inositol.
The simplest member of the class of 7-hydroxyisoflavones that is isoflavone with a hydroxy substituent at position 7.
A methoxyisoflavone that is isoflavone substituted by a methoxy group at position 7.

An <element>N</element>-acetyl-<stereo>beta</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-glucosaminyl group having an <stereo>alpha</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-galactosyl-(1<arrow>right</arrow>3)-<stereo>beta</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-galactosyl moiety attached at the 4-position.
The <stereo>beta</stereo>-anomer of <stereo>D</stereo>-fructofuranose 2-phosphate.

An <element>N</element>-acetyl-<stereo>D</stereo>-glucosaminyl group obtained by removing the hydroxy group from the hemiacetal function of <stereo>beta</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-galactosyl-(1<arrow>right</arrow>4)-<element>N</element>-acetyl-<stereo>beta</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-glucosamine. Proposed epitope of paragloboside (<stereo>beta</stereo>1<arrow>right</arrow>4).
A group obtained by removing the hydroxy group from the hemiacetal function of <stereo>beta</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-mannose.
The <stereo>beta</stereo>-anomer of <stereo>L</stereo>-fucose 1-phosphate.
An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of indol-3-ylacetic acid.
An  aliphatic aldehyde obtained by formal oxygenation of one of the terminal methyl groups of any straight-chain alkane.
The <stereo>trans</stereo>-isomer of 2-coumarate.
The <stereo>trans</stereo>-isomer of 4-coumarate.
A galactonate compound having <stereo>D</stereo>-configuration.
An <locant>alpha</locant>-amino-acid anion that is the conjugate base of <stereo>L</stereo>-aspartic 4-semialdehyde, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.
The <stereo>L</stereo>-enantiomer of gulonate.
A ribonucleoside 3'-monophosphate(2<minus/>) oxoanion in which both of the acidic hydroxy groups from the phosphate moiety are deprotonated.
A fatty acid ethyl ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of a long-chain fatty acid with the hydroxy group of ethanol.
Synonyms: a long-chain fatty acyl ethyl ester

Definition: Any aromatic amide obtained by acylation of aniline.
A GDP-<stereo>L</stereo>-fucose in which the anomeric oxygen is on the same side of the fucose ring as the methyl substituent.
A UDP-amino sugar having <stereo>alpha</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-glucosamine as the amino-sugar component.
A 3-oxo steroid that has <stereo>alpha</stereo> configuration at position 5.
A sterol ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of any carboxylic acid with the 3-hydroxy group of a 3<stereo>beta</stereo>-hydroxysterol.
Any hydroxy carboxylic acid which contains a hydroxy substituent <locant>gamma</locant> to a carboxy group.
Any member of the class of pteridines in which the the pteridine ring has been reduced by the formal addition of one molecule of hydrogen to positions 6 and 7.
A 3-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of acetoacetic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.
An acyl monophosphate(1<minus/>) that is the conjugate base of acetyl dihydrogen phosphate.
An <element>O</element>-acyl carbohydrate consisting of maltose carrying an anomeric <element>O</element>-acetyl substituent.
A benzoate that is the conjugate base of acetylsalicylic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.
An enal obtained by formal dehydrogenation across positions 2 and 3 of any <ital>n</ital>-alkanal
Any primary amine in which the substituent attached to nitrogen is an alkyl group.
An acetamide where at at least one of the amide hydrogens is substituted by an aryl group. RNHAc where R is an aryl group.
Any hydroxylamine where the nitrogen is attached directly to an aryl group.
An <element>S</element>-hydrocarbyl-<stereo>L</stereo>-cysteine in which the hydrocarbyl component can be any polyprenyl group.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion that is obtained by removal of a proton from both of the carboxylic acid groups of citramalic acid.
A long-chain fatty acid anion and the conjugate base of crepenynic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid group.
The <stereo>D</stereo>-enantiomer of dTDP-galactose.
A pyranone obtained by selective hydrogenation of the 4a,5-double bond in monacolin L.
An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of ferulic acid.
Any glycosyloxyflavone that consists of a flavonol attached to a glycosyl residue at position 3 via a glycosidic linkage.
An aldehyde that is acetaldehyde in which one of the hydrogens of the methyl group is replaced by fluorine.
An <locant>alpha</locant>-amino-acid anion that is the conjugate base of glutamic acid, having anionic carboxy groups and a cationic amino group
A glycerol monophosphate having the phosphate group located at position 1.
An arsenic oxoanion obtained deprotonation of both arsenite OH groups of methylarsonous acid.
A <locant>beta</locant>-diketone that is pentane in which the hydrogens at positions 2 and 4 are replaced by oxo groups.
